Certainly! Here's a list of simple and commonly used commands in the 
Ubuntu terminal. These commands are fundamental for navigating and
manipulating files, system information, and basic networking in Ubuntu.

    Navigating the File System:
        pwd: Prints the current directory.
        ls: Lists files in the current directory.
        cd directory: Changes the current directory to directory.
        cd ..: Moves up one directory level.
        cd ~: Changes to the home directory.

    File and Directory Operations:
        touch filename: Creates a new empty file named filename.
        mkdir directory: Creates a new directory named directory.
        rm file: Deletes a file (use -r for a directory).
        cp source destination: Copies a file or directory.
        mv source destination: Moves or renames a file or directory.

    Viewing and Editing Files:
        cat file: Displays the content of a file.
        less file: Views the content of a file one screen at a time.
        nano file: Opens a file in the nano text editor.
        head file: Shows the first 10 lines of a file.
        tail file: Shows the last 10 lines of a file (use -f to follow added lines).

    System Information and Management:
        top: Displays ongoing look at processor activity in real-time.
        df: Shows disk usage.
        free: Displays memory usage.
        uname -a: Shows system information.
        ps: Displays information about current processes.

    Networking:
        ping host: Pings a network host.
        ifconfig or ip addr: Displays network configuration.
        netstat: Displays network connections.
        wget url: Downloads a file from the internet.

    Package Management (using APT):
        sudo apt update: Updates the package list.
        sudo apt upgrade: Upgrades all upgradable packages.
        sudo apt install package: Installs a package.
        sudo apt remove package: Removes a package.

    File Permissions:
        chmod permissions file: Changes the permissions of a file.
        chown user:group file: Changes the owner and group of a file.

    Archiving and Compression:
        tar -czvf name.tar.gz directory/: Compresses a directory to a tar.gz file.
        tar -xzvf file.tar.gz: Extracts a tar.gz file.

    Searching and Finding:
        grep pattern files: Searches for a pattern in files.
        find: Searches for files in a directory hierarchy.

    System Shutdown and Restart:
        shutdown now: Shuts down the system.
        reboot: Restarts the system.
